00:08:36,770 --> 00:08:38,688
I'll… I'll have to adjust a
few of my references,

251
00:08:38,772 --> 00:08:40,690
but you have to be able
to read an audience, right?

252
00:08:40,774 --> 00:08:42,108
Uh-huh.

253
00:08:42,192 --> 00:08:43,860
Uh, hey, are there large
quantities of narcotics

254
00:08:43,944 --> 00:08:45,070
in these Abba-Zabas of yours?

255
00:08:45,154 --> 00:08:46,363
I can't explain. I…

256
00:08:46,447 --> 00:08:47,864
Just… Just come and you'll see. Friday.

257
00:08:47,948 --> 00:08:51,284
-Oh, I can't. I have plans.
-What plans?

258
00:08:51,368 --> 00:08:54,121
Uh, to not be bored or
miserable at some old fuck's party.

259
00:08:54,205 --> 00:08:56,707
Come. You'll… You'll watch,
you'll see, you'll understand.

260
00:08:56,791 --> 00:08:57,958
I'll… I'll call you with the address.

261
00:08:58,042 --> 00:08:59,294
Wear something… clean.

262
00:09:06,134 --> 00:09:07,802
ABE: All right, everybody.

263
00:09:07,886 --> 00:09:09,261
Time's up.

264
00:09:09,345 --> 00:09:11,097
Put your papers on my desk

265
00:09:11,181 --> 00:09:13,474
if they contain the correct answers,

266
00:09:13,558 --> 00:09:16,227
otherwise, just don't.

267
00:09:16,311 --> 00:09:18,729
-Abe.
-Oh, hello, Irving.

268
00:09:18,813 --> 00:09:20,064
What's up?

269
00:09:20,148 --> 00:09:21,565
I want you to meet Charles Connelly,

270
00:09:21,649 --> 00:09:24,193
Executive Recruiter from Bell Labs.

271
00:09:24,277 --> 00:09:25,611
Bell Labs.

272
00:09:25,695 --> 00:09:26,987
You got time to talk?

273
00:09:27,071 --> 00:09:28,864
Uh, sure.

274
00:09:28,948 --> 00:09:30,699
We're calling it Project Echo, Abe.

275
00:09:30,783 --> 00:09:33,495
A quantum leap in satellite technology.

276
00:09:33,579 --> 00:09:35,163
The commercial ramifications
of this could be huge.

277
00:09:35,247 --> 00:09:36,998
Not to mention its defense capabilities.

278
00:09:37,082 --> 00:09:39,459
IRVING: It would revolutionize
the communications industry.

279
00:09:39,543 --> 00:09:41,128
CHARLES: And Bell
Labs is leading the pack.

280
00:09:41,212 --> 00:09:42,462
Abe, we're gathering
the best and the brightest

281
00:09:42,546 --> 00:09:43,922
to help us get there first.

282
00:09:44,006 --> 00:09:46,299
-May I stop you there?
-CHARLES: Of course.

283
00:09:46,383 --> 00:09:49,386
I want no part of Sputnik panic.

284
00:09:49,470 --> 00:09:50,595
This smacks of that.

285
00:09:50,679 --> 00:09:52,180
There's no panic, Abe.

286
00:09:52,264 --> 00:09:53,265
We're doing this right.

287
00:09:53,349 --> 00:09:54,474
We never rush R&D.

288
00:09:54,558 --> 00:09:55,559
Your colleague, Bill Chernik…

289
00:09:55,643 --> 00:09:56,935
Bill and Abe have known
each other a long time.

290
00:09:57,019 --> 00:09:59,020
Bill Chernik's a good man.

291
00:09:59,104 --> 00:10:00,605
CHARLES: He's been
consulting with us for a while.

292
00:10:00,689 --> 00:10:02,399
Ask him about us.
You'll like what you hear.

293
00:10:02,483 --> 00:10:04,109
There's no way this could work.

294
00:10:04,193 --> 00:10:06,027
My class load is so full.

295
00:10:06,111 --> 00:10:08,071
We can help with that.
Take things off your plate.

296
00:10:08,155 --> 00:10:10,490
No, I'm loath to do that.

297
00:10:10,574 --> 00:10:12,076
CHARLES: We'll work around your schedule.

298
00:10:12,160 --> 00:10:13,870
An applied mathematician of your skills

299
00:10:13,954 --> 00:10:15,496
is in high demand these days.

300
00:10:15,580 --> 00:10:17,373
-We need you.
-[CHUCKLES]

301
00:10:17,457 --> 00:10:19,167
I told you he'd be a tough sell.

302
00:10:19,251 --> 00:10:20,751
Which makes us want you more.

303
00:10:20,835 --> 00:10:22,044
Pending a security clearance,

304
00:10:22,128 --> 00:10:23,463
Bell Labs is at your beck and call.

305
00:10:23,547 --> 00:10:24,505
I need to get home.

306
00:10:24,589 --> 00:10:26,132
Let me walk with you.

307
00:10:26,216 --> 00:10:27,758
-[BELL TOLLS]
-Please think it over.

308
00:10:27,842 --> 00:10:29,802
Take some time.
And call with any questions.

309
00:10:29,886 --> 00:10:31,596
-I doubt I'll have any.
-Call anyhow.

310
00:10:31,680 --> 00:10:33,264
I'll give you the pitch all over again.

311
00:10:33,348 --> 00:10:35,349
And thanks for your time.

312
00:10:35,433 --> 00:10:37,102
See you Monday, Abe.

313
00:10:40,105 --> 00:10:42,398
We're going out to dinner!

314
00:10:42,482 --> 00:10:43,566
ROSE: Abe?

315
00:10:43,650 --> 00:10:46,068
Rose, Rose, get in here.

316
00:10:46,152 --> 00:10:48,070
We are going out to dinner.

317
00:10:48,154 --> 00:10:51,158
Ruby Foo's, Le Pavillon, name it.

318
00:10:51,242 --> 00:10:53,202
Abe, slow down.
Why are we going out to dinner?

319
00:10:53,286 --> 00:10:54,870
Bell Labs, Rose.

320
00:10:54,954 --> 00:10:56,997
I got an offer to work at Bell Labs.

321
00:10:57,081 --> 00:10:59,082
-What?
-Bell Labs down in the village!

322
00:10:59,166 --> 00:11:00,542
Oh, my God, Abe!

323
00:11:00,626 --> 00:11:03,670
-[LAUGHING]
-Oh, oh.

324
00:11:03,754 --> 00:11:06,840
You should have seen
me with that recruiter.

325
00:11:06,924 --> 00:11:08,926
I played it so cool.

326
00:11:09,010 --> 00:11:10,969
I kind of nodded like this,

327
00:11:11,053 --> 00:11:12,429
was shaking my head a little bit.

328
00:11:12,513 --> 00:11:14,056
Very serious, very dubious.

329
00:11:14,140 --> 00:11:16,725
Oh, you can look
extremely dubious. [LAUGHS]

330
00:11:16,809 --> 00:11:19,061
And he was eating out
of the palm of my hand.

331
00:11:19,145 --> 00:11:21,271
This is the big leagues, Rose.

332
00:11:21,355 --> 00:11:24,816
This… this is the hotbed of invention.

333
00:11:24,900 --> 00:11:27,736
That TV that you all like so much,

334
00:11:27,820 --> 00:11:31,407
-courtesy of Bell Labs transistor work.
-No.

335
00:11:31,491 --> 00:11:33,618
-ETHAN: Grandpa, I was watching that.
-Oh.

336
00:11:33,702 --> 00:11:38,122
Bardeen and Brattain and
Shockley won a Nobel for that.

337
00:11:38,206 --> 00:11:40,208
And now I am in their ranks.

338
00:11:40,292 --> 00:11:41,918
Where are we going for dinner?

339
00:11:42,002 --> 00:11:43,336
What about a dinner?

340
00:11:43,420 --> 00:11:44,754
We're going out. The whole family.

341
00:11:44,838 --> 00:11:46,047
Call Noah and Astrid.

342
00:11:46,131 --> 00:11:48,883
He's got an offer from Bell Labs.

343
00:11:48,967 --> 00:11:51,261
-Wow, Papa, congratulations.
-[LAUGHS]

344
00:11:51,345 --> 00:11:52,845
Thank you very much.

345
00:11:52,929 --> 00:11:54,347
You've been obsessing on Bell Labs

346
00:11:54,431 --> 00:11:55,974
-for, like, 20 years now.
-Mm-hmm.

347
00:11:56,058 --> 00:11:57,392
I haven't been obsessing on them.

348
00:11:57,476 --> 00:11:59,269
My whole childhood, it was
Bell Labs this and Bell Labs that,

349
00:11:59,353 --> 00:12:00,937
and, "My God, I'd give up pastrami

350
00:12:01,021 --> 00:12:02,188
for a job at Bell Labs."

351
00:12:02,272 --> 00:12:03,523
[LAUGHS] I may have mentioned them.

352
00:12:03,607 --> 00:12:05,066
A… And once a year, we'd
tour the building? The outside,

353
00:12:05,150 --> 00:12:06,442
-because we weren't allowed in.
-You kids would play

354
00:12:06,526 --> 00:12:08,111
on the sidewalk while your
father would jump up and down,

355
00:12:08,195 --> 00:12:09,446
-and try and peek in the windows.
-Yes.

356
00:12:09,530 --> 00:12:11,490
That may have happened once or twice.

357
00:12:11,574 --> 00:12:13,158
-[CHUCKLES]
-Is that my blouse?

358
00:12:13,242 --> 00:12:15,286
-Uh, yes, but it's not quite right.
-For what?

359
00:12:15,370 --> 00:12:18,414
Okay, I… I'm talking about
very important things here,

360
00:12:18,498 --> 00:12:20,332
and you're talking about clothes.

361
00:12:20,416 --> 00:12:23,752
I have to get dressed.
Congratulations, Papa.

362
00:12:23,836 --> 00:12:26,046
How often do I get a job at Bell Labs

363
00:12:26,130 --> 00:12:28,882
and no one wants to celebrate with me?

364
00:12:28,966 --> 00:12:31,760
Oh, Abe, my love, we will find
the perfect night to celebrate.

365
00:12:31,844 --> 00:12:33,304
With Noah and Astrid?

366
00:12:33,388 --> 00:12:34,513
Uh, they will be there.

367
00:12:34,597 --> 00:12:35,931
I mean, it's Bell Labs.

368
00:12:36,015 --> 00:12:38,642
And we, we are all so very proud of you.

369
00:12:38,726 --> 00:12:40,185
Mama, where's your green dress?

370
00:12:40,269 --> 00:12:41,186
At the cleaners.

371
00:12:41,270 --> 00:12:42,730
[WHISPERS]: Oh, shoot.

372
00:12:45,858 --> 00:12:47,943
I'm never sure about me and peach.

373
00:12:48,027 --> 00:12:50,656
Hmm. I am.

374
00:12:52,741 --> 00:12:53,867
Here.

375
00:12:53,951 --> 00:12:54,993
The Dior?

376
00:12:55,077 --> 00:12:56,620
Oh, that's perfect.

377
00:12:56,704 --> 00:13:00,415
-So, you're going to another party.
-Hmm?

378
00:13:00,499 --> 00:13:02,542
That's the fourth
one this week, isn't it?

379
00:13:02,626 --> 00:13:04,669
Four this week, three last week.

380
00:13:04,753 --> 00:13:06,129
Which, of course, means
they've already seen

381
00:13:06,213 --> 00:13:07,339
everything in my closet.

382
00:13:07,423 --> 00:13:08,882
Enter yours.

383
00:13:08,966 --> 00:13:12,719
So, are these friends
of yours and Joel's?

384
00:13:12,803 --> 00:13:14,721
No. New friends.

385
00:13:14,805 --> 00:13:16,097
-Girls from work.
-Hmm.

386
00:13:16,181 --> 00:13:17,557
What do you think?

387
00:13:17,641 --> 00:13:19,726
Lovely, understated.

388
00:13:19,810 --> 00:13:21,227
-Understated?
-Mm-hmm.

389
00:13:21,311 --> 00:13:23,730
-Next.
-You don't want to be understated?

390
00:13:23,814 --> 00:13:25,023
MIDGE: I need to stand out.

391
00:13:25,107 --> 00:13:26,441
ROSE: Well, you always stand out.

392
00:13:26,525 --> 00:13:28,319
I need to stand out
in a very specific way.

393
00:13:28,403 --> 00:13:29,695
Well, you could wear nothing.

394
00:13:29,779 --> 00:13:31,322
That would get some sort of attention.

395
00:13:31,406 --> 00:13:32,657
Don't I know it.

396
00:13:32,741 --> 00:13:35,284
Now, tell me about… not until my funeral.

397
00:13:35,368 --> 00:13:39,664
So tell me, are there
men at these, uh, parties?

398
00:13:39,748 --> 00:13:41,707
They aren't nun parties, Mama.

399
00:13:41,791 --> 00:13:44,001
Well, you know, a girl
standing alone at a party

400
00:13:44,085 --> 00:13:45,753
-says just one thing.
-What's that?

401
00:13:45,837 --> 00:13:47,171
-I'm prey. Hunt me.
-Perfect.

402
00:13:47,255 --> 00:13:48,756
-Miriam.
-No, seriously,

403
00:13:48,840 --> 00:13:50,508
I was looking for a catchphrase.
That's it.

404
00:13:50,592 --> 00:13:51,926
You should wait to go to these parties.

405
00:13:52,010 --> 00:13:53,135
It's too soon.

406
00:13:53,219 --> 00:13:54,512
I'll add some gloves to this.

407
00:13:54,596 --> 00:13:55,930
That should give it some zazz.

408
00:13:56,014 --> 00:13:57,556
-Miriam…
-Thanks for the dress, Mama.

409
00:13:57,640 --> 00:13:59,601
ROSE: Oh…

410
00:14:08,068 --> 00:14:09,194
What are you doing here?

411
00:14:09,278 --> 00:14:10,487
What am I…

412
00:14:10,571 --> 00:14:12,072
Yo… You invited me to this stupid party.

413
00:14:12,156 --> 00:14:13,156
No, I mean on the elevator.

414
00:14:13,240 --> 00:14:14,825
You're not leaving, are you?

415
00:14:14,909 --> 00:14:16,660
No, I've been riding this
thing up and down for an hour

416
00:14:16,744 --> 00:14:18,120
waiting for you to float in here

417
00:14:18,204 --> 00:14:19,788
on your golden fucking Icarus horse.

418
00:14:19,872 --> 00:14:21,331
You got a pretty loose
concept of time, lady.

419
00:14:21,415 --> 00:14:22,958
Cabs were scarce.

420
00:14:23,042 --> 00:14:24,418
Well, are you waiting for
an engraved invitation?

421
00:14:24,502 --> 00:14:25,711
Get in here.

422
00:14:28,380 --> 00:14:30,090
Got to know the building pretty well.

423
00:14:30,174 --> 00:14:31,717
Old guy on six has cancer.

424
00:14:31,801 --> 00:14:33,135
Oh, that's terrible.

425
00:14:33,219 --> 00:14:35,011
I inspired him to reach
out to his daughter.

426
00:14:35,095 --> 00:14:36,596
They've been on the
outs since she divorced.

427
00:14:36,680 --> 00:14:37,848
She's here now, cooking for him.

428
00:14:37,932 --> 00:14:38,974
That's nice.

429
00:14:39,058 --> 00:14:40,684
Oh, you hear that?

430
00:14:40,768 --> 00:14:42,477
Couple on the fourth
floor, they've been fighting

431
00:14:42,561 --> 00:14:43,979
for a full half hour.

432
00:14:44,063 --> 00:14:46,022
He pinched some girl's ass, she saw.

433
00:14:46,106 --> 00:14:48,109
May have been the cancer guy's daughter.

434
00:14:48,193 --> 00:14:50,361
Oh, I hope she did
nothing to encourage that.

435
00:14:50,445 --> 00:14:51,446
[ELEVATOR BELL DINGS]

436
00:14:51,530 --> 00:14:52,572
You look nice, by the way.

437
00:14:52,656 --> 00:14:53,698
Thanks.

438
00:14:53,782 --> 00:14:54,949
Clean shirt?

439
00:14:55,033 --> 00:14:56,534
Uh, define "clean."

440
00:14:56,618 --> 00:14:59,746
[INDISTINCT CHATTER, SOFT MUSIC PLAYING]

441
00:14:59,830 --> 00:15:02,373
Okay, this is the worst
party I've ever been to.

442
00:15:02,457 --> 00:15:04,751
We just walked in the door.

443
00:15:04,835 --> 00:15:06,419
Let's go get a hot dog or something.

444
00:15:06,503 --> 00:15:08,671
No, no, no, stay.

445
00:15:08,755 --> 00:15:10,339
-Midge, hi.
-Hi, Mary.

446
00:15:10,423 --> 00:15:12,175
This is my friend, Susie. Susie, Mary.

447
00:15:12,259 --> 00:15:14,343
Hi, Susie, come on in. Meet the others.

448
00:15:14,427 --> 00:15:15,970
Eh, I feel like I got it.

449
00:15:16,054 --> 00:15:17,096
I'll see you inside, Mary.

450
00:15:17,180 --> 00:15:19,724
Nice meeting you.

451
00:15:19,808 --> 00:15:21,893
-What a drip.
-You're the drip.

452
00:15:21,977 --> 00:15:23,686
Come on, get with the program here.

453
00:15:23,770 --> 00:15:26,106
Why would anyone in their
right mind go to parties?

454
00:15:26,190 --> 00:15:27,900
I mean, just buy some
Sno Balls and a beer,

455
00:15:27,984 --> 00:15:30,611
and take the subway at
rush hour, same fucking thing.

456
00:15:30,695 --> 00:15:32,446
I… I'm sorry, I just don't get it.

457
00:15:32,530 --> 00:15:34,490
Midge, I think I'm in love.

458
00:15:34,574 --> 00:15:37,159
-Not again.
-Come see him, tell me if I'm crazy.

459
00:15:37,243 --> 00:15:38,285
He's my dad's boss.

460
00:15:38,369 --> 00:15:39,787
He's 70.

461
00:15:39,871 --> 00:15:42,039
And deaf and married,
but keep an open mind.

462
00:15:42,123 --> 00:15:43,457
That's my cue.

463
00:15:43,541 --> 00:15:44,666
Huh?

464
00:15:44,750 --> 00:15:46,919
[APPLAUSE]

465
00:15:48,629 --> 00:15:50,631
Wait a minute.

466
00:15:51,674 --> 00:15:55,093
Wait a minute.

467
00:15:55,177 --> 00:15:57,221
I get it. I get it.

468
00:15:57,305 --> 00:15:59,348
Mary? I get it.

469
00:15:59,432 --> 00:16:01,016
MIDGE: Wow, your silver anniversary.

470
00:16:01,100 --> 00:16:02,726
Your husband looks thrilled.

471
00:16:02,810 --> 00:16:06,105
Maybe we do need a
better motivator for men

472
00:16:06,189 --> 00:16:08,566
to get them to care about
the silver anniversary.

473
00:16:08,650 --> 00:16:10,485
Because what man
really cares about silver?

474
00:16:10,569 --> 00:16:14,072
Maybe 25 years is the Yankees
season tickets anniversary.

475
00:16:14,156 --> 00:16:16,032
-[LAUGHTER]
-Yeah!

476
00:16:16,116 --> 00:16:17,700
Yeah, and then to get them to 50,

477
00:16:17,784 --> 00:16:19,452
we need something really good.

478
00:16:19,536 --> 00:16:21,830
Maybe it's the "another
woman's boobs" anniversary.

479
00:16:21,914 --> 00:16:23,957
-[LAUGHTER]
-Mm-hmm.

480
00:16:24,041 --> 00:16:27,794
Me, personally, I… I was
never great at gift-giving.

481
00:16:27,878 --> 00:16:30,630
Maybe it's because I never
got to celebrate Christmas.

482
00:16:30,714 --> 00:16:32,632
-I got Hanukkah.
-[SOFT LAUGHTER]

483
00:16:32,716 --> 00:16:34,342
Doesn't exactly prepare you the same way.

484
00:16:34,426 --> 00:16:36,469
For Christmas, a gentile would get a bike

485
00:16:36,553 --> 00:16:38,596
as a reminder that
their parents love them.

486
00:16:38,680 --> 00:16:41,057
For Hanukkah, we would get socks

487
00:16:41,141 --> 00:16:43,268
as a reminder that we were persecuted.

488
00:16:43,352 --> 00:16:45,271
[LAUGHTER]

489
00:16:46,814 --> 00:16:48,691
Hey. You look happy.

490
00:16:48,775 --> 00:16:49,817
As a clam.

491
00:16:49,901 --> 00:16:51,110
I ate all the clams, by the way.

492
00:16:51,194 --> 00:16:52,653
See? Parties aren't so bad.

493
00:16:52,737 --> 00:16:54,363
Hmm.
I'm just trying to figure out the best way

494
00:16:54,447 --> 00:16:55,948
to hide a lobster under my hat.

495
00:16:56,032 --> 00:16:57,908
-So, did you catch my set?
-Your what?

496
00:16:57,992 --> 00:16:59,785
Just now. You hear all the laughs I got?

497
00:16:59,869 --> 00:17:01,161
Yeah, I heard the laughs.

498
00:17:01,245 --> 00:17:02,329
Pretty funny, right?

499
00:17:02,413 --> 00:17:03,497
You're a funny woman.

500
00:17:03,581 --> 00:17:05,082
Could you pass the asparagus?

501
00:17:05,166 --> 00:17:07,543
I did a version of the Hanukkah
run a couple weeks ago,

502
00:17:07,627 --> 00:17:09,211
but I've honed it a lot since then.

503
00:17:09,295 --> 00:17:11,171
Yeah, that was some
top-notch honing, there.

504
00:17:11,255 --> 00:17:13,465
RANDALL: Darling? Darling, over here!

