00:25:15,042 --> 00:25:16,795
Really, Astrid, my
arms are getting tired.

749
00:25:16,879 --> 00:25:18,671
-Please put those down.
-It's just that your apartment's

750
00:25:18,755 --> 00:25:20,298
so beautiful, and I
know you like everything

751
00:25:20,382 --> 00:25:22,425
in a certain way, so maybe
Noah can just take them

752
00:25:22,509 --> 00:25:24,386
back to the car until
the kids get home, or…

753
00:25:24,470 --> 00:25:26,054
-Give this to me.
-Oh, thank you.

754
00:25:26,138 --> 00:25:27,555
What's in the bag?

755
00:25:27,639 --> 00:25:28,890
Gefilte fish.

756
00:25:28,974 --> 00:25:31,434
-My next guess.
-I tried a new recipe.

757
00:25:31,518 --> 00:25:34,312
You'll be very happy…
there are no onions in this one, Rose.

758
00:25:34,396 --> 00:25:36,189
"Happy" doesn't quite describe it.

759
00:25:36,273 --> 00:25:38,108
-I'll take it, ma'am.
-Thank you, Zelda.

760
00:25:38,192 --> 00:25:40,110
-You know where to…
-Yes, I do.

761
00:25:40,194 --> 00:25:41,778
[SIGHS]: Here. This is for you.

762
00:25:41,862 --> 00:25:43,863
Honestly, Astrid, you
don't have to bring us gifts

763
00:25:43,947 --> 00:25:45,532
every time you go to Israel.

764
00:25:45,616 --> 00:25:47,909
-I…
-What was this, your sixth, seventh trip?

765
00:25:47,993 --> 00:25:49,285
-11th. [GIGGLES]
-MIDGE: Oh.

766
00:25:49,369 --> 00:25:52,330
Can't get enough of the Holy Land.

767
00:25:52,414 --> 00:25:55,417
[ABE AND NOAH TALKING IN DISTANCE]

768
00:25:55,501 --> 00:25:59,130
-What a beautiful mezuzah.
-[ASTRID LAUGHS]

769
00:25:59,214 --> 00:26:01,799
I'd never seen one that big before.
[LAUGHS]

770
00:26:01,883 --> 00:26:04,135
It looks like it ate all
the other mezuzahs.

771
00:26:04,219 --> 00:26:05,469
Is that bad?

772
00:26:05,553 --> 00:26:07,596
-Oh. No.
-I could return it.

773
00:26:07,680 --> 00:26:10,474
-To Israel?
-Rose, Bell Labs has two cafeterias.

774
00:26:10,558 --> 00:26:12,226
Different cuisines in each one.

775
00:26:12,310 --> 00:26:14,103
I can choose. I get to choose.

776
00:26:14,187 --> 00:26:15,771
I better start easing them out,

777
00:26:15,855 --> 00:26:17,805
or they'll lose all interest in dinner.

778
00:26:18,733 --> 00:26:20,693
I brought you a gift, too.

779
00:26:20,777 --> 00:26:22,736
Is it another giant mezuzah?

780
00:26:22,820 --> 00:26:24,738
Oh, it is such a stupid gift.

781
00:26:24,822 --> 00:26:26,740
-Astrid, no.
-No, Rose has a mezuzah.

782
00:26:26,824 --> 00:26:28,826
You have a mezuzah. It's not shoes

783
00:26:28,910 --> 00:26:30,953
you can't just change
them out every season.

784
00:26:31,037 --> 00:26:33,456
No, but if we ever move
to a very big house…

785
00:26:33,540 --> 00:26:35,459
Oh, I just wish Rose liked me.

786
00:26:35,543 --> 00:26:37,711
She likes you very much.
She loves you, Astrid.

787
00:26:37,795 --> 00:26:39,671
-I make her nervous.
-Breathing makes her nervous.

788
00:26:39,755 --> 00:26:41,423
I thought that converting would help.

789
00:26:41,507 --> 00:26:43,717
I know that it's hard having
an outsider in your family.

790
00:26:43,801 --> 00:26:45,510
You are not an outsider.

791
00:26:45,594 --> 00:26:47,429
-Mm-mm. I heard comments at our wedding.
-No one commented.

792
00:26:47,513 --> 00:26:49,181
"What's up with the shiksa Noah married?"

793
00:26:49,265 --> 00:26:52,392
-Aunt Gertie, once.
-I'm an outsider. I'm barren.

794
00:26:52,476 --> 00:26:53,518
Astrid, you're young.

795
00:26:53,602 --> 00:26:55,228
No, I'm not. I'm 30.

796
00:26:55,312 --> 00:26:56,855
We're seeing the fertility
doctor again tomorrow.

797
00:26:56,939 --> 00:27:00,025
He's one of the pioneers in
cervical cap inseminations.

798
00:27:00,109 --> 00:27:01,485
Well, everyone looks good in a cap.

799
00:27:01,569 --> 00:27:02,944
I'm almost too afraid to go.

800
00:27:03,028 --> 00:27:04,988
I mean, what if it
doesn't work this time?

801
00:27:05,072 --> 00:27:07,282
What methods did you and
Joel use to get pregnant?

802
00:27:07,366 --> 00:27:09,868
Well… sex.

803
00:27:09,952 --> 00:27:13,205
Yeah, that seems to work for most people.

804
00:27:13,289 --> 00:27:14,289
Oh, honey…

805
00:27:14,373 --> 00:27:15,583
Seven years of trying. I mean,

806
00:27:15,667 --> 00:27:16,876
[WHISPERS] what if he leaves me?

807
00:27:16,960 --> 00:27:18,336
Noah is not going to leave you.

808
00:27:18,420 --> 00:27:21,047
You did everything perfectly,
and that <i>yutz</i> left you.

809
00:27:21,131 --> 00:27:22,757
Noah loves you.

810
00:27:22,841 --> 00:27:24,509
And I know you think he's pretty dreamy,

811
00:27:24,593 --> 00:27:26,886
but I'm his sister, so I
can tell you the truth.

812
00:27:26,970 --> 00:27:27,125
Oh.

813
00:27:27,209 --> 00:27:30,014
He's a big nerd who
lucked out and married up.

814
00:27:30,098 --> 00:27:32,016
-[SIGHS] No.
-Seriously. You're saving him

815
00:27:32,100 --> 00:27:34,435
-from a sad, lonely life in a lab.
-[LAUGHS]

816
00:27:34,519 --> 00:27:36,187
He's not going anywhere. Okay?

817
00:27:36,271 --> 00:27:38,981
-ROSE: Miriam! Astrid! We're leaving!
-Okay.

818
00:27:39,065 --> 00:27:40,441
Okay.

819
00:27:40,525 --> 00:27:42,902
[INDISTINCT CHATTER
CONTINUES IN DISTANCE]

820
00:27:48,366 --> 00:27:52,078
♪♪

821
00:27:52,162 --> 00:27:54,289
ABE: This is the eighth grade,

822
00:27:54,373 --> 00:27:56,333
and Miss Bedetsky is so overloaded

823
00:27:56,417 --> 00:27:58,126
with math homework to grade,

824
00:27:58,210 --> 00:27:59,169
I offered to help.

825
00:27:59,253 --> 00:28:00,712
I was new to her class,

826
00:28:00,796 --> 00:28:02,089
and she thought it was cute

827
00:28:02,173 --> 00:28:04,258
that a 13-year-old would offer to help.

828
00:28:04,342 --> 00:28:06,218
The emphasis on
education in the Jewish faith

829
00:28:06,302 --> 00:28:09,137
may be the thing that I admire the most.

830
00:28:09,221 --> 00:28:10,931
Anyway, she let me try.

831
00:28:11,015 --> 00:28:13,058
And I graded them perfectly

832
00:28:13,142 --> 00:28:15,185
without even using the key.

833
00:28:15,269 --> 00:28:18,188
She looked at me,
astonished, and then said,

834
00:28:18,272 --> 00:28:21,108
"Abraham Weissman, you are a natural born

835
00:28:21,192 --> 00:28:22,776
-mathematician."
-Mm.

836
00:28:22,860 --> 00:28:24,027
I was so proud.

837
00:28:24,111 --> 00:28:26,029
[LAUGHS] Did you stay in touch with her?

838
00:28:26,113 --> 00:28:27,614
-That moron? No.
-ROSE: Abe.

839
00:28:27,698 --> 00:28:29,825
What? There were mistakes she didn't find

840
00:28:29,909 --> 00:28:31,743
in the papers she graded that day.

841
00:28:31,827 --> 00:28:33,287
So I corrected them and
immediately transferred

842
00:28:33,371 --> 00:28:35,081
-out of her class.
-He couldn't just stop

843
00:28:35,165 --> 00:28:37,083
at the nice part…
he just, he had to keep going.

844
00:28:37,167 --> 00:28:39,544
She left the school after
that, on my recommendation.

845
00:28:39,628 --> 00:28:41,588
I would like to propose a toast.
[CLEARS THROAT]

846
00:28:41,672 --> 00:28:43,673
-ASTRID: Mmm.
-I have never understood

847
00:28:43,757 --> 00:28:46,509
what Abe Weissman was
talking about ever in my life.

848
00:28:46,593 --> 00:28:48,803
One time I made the mistake
of asking about his day.

849
00:28:48,887 --> 00:28:50,263
45 minutes later, he was still talking,

850
00:28:50,347 --> 00:28:51,806
but I had taken to my bed.

851
00:28:51,890 --> 00:28:53,975
-[LAUGHING]
-So for both of our sakes,

852
00:28:54,059 --> 00:28:56,019
I'm very glad that he's finally found

853
00:28:56,103 --> 00:28:58,521
some people who truly speak his language.

854
00:28:58,605 --> 00:29:01,524
And apparently whatever he's
been saying is very impressive.

855
00:29:01,608 --> 00:29:04,527
So please join me in toasting my father,

856
00:29:04,611 --> 00:29:07,363
-the great Abe Weissman.
-NOAH: Cheers.

857
00:29:07,447 --> 00:29:09,324
L'chaim!

858
00:29:09,408 --> 00:29:11,243
[MIDGE CLEARS THROAT]

859
00:29:22,588 --> 00:29:25,132
-What do we do?
-We should leave.

860
00:29:25,216 --> 00:29:27,217
-We're not leaving.
-He's practically on top of us.

861
00:29:27,301 --> 00:29:28,218
Wait, is that the secretary?

862
00:29:28,302 --> 00:29:29,303
There are a thousand restaurants

863
00:29:29,387 --> 00:29:30,763
in the city… what are the odds?

864
00:29:30,847 --> 00:29:31,930
One in sixteen thousand,
four hundred fifty…

865
00:29:32,014 --> 00:29:33,223
Twelve thousand, three hundred…

866
00:29:33,307 --> 00:29:34,850
I'm taking into account weather effects,

867
00:29:34,934 --> 00:29:36,518
that some restaurants
are closed on Mondays…

868
00:29:36,602 --> 00:29:38,103
Yeah, yeah, but I'm calculating
differentials in geography,

869
00:29:38,187 --> 00:29:40,272
-quality…
-We get it, guys, the odds are low.

870
00:29:40,356 --> 00:29:41,398
She doesn't even look Jewish.

871
00:29:41,482 --> 00:29:42,816
-Is she Jewish or…
-We should leave.

872
00:29:42,900 --> 00:29:44,276
Papa, this is your celebration.

873
00:29:44,360 --> 00:29:45,778
Don't let him ruin it.

874
00:29:45,862 --> 00:29:47,071
I couldn't find my Finchley cuff links.

875
00:29:47,155 --> 00:29:49,031
It was an omen. I should have heeded it.

876
00:29:49,115 --> 00:29:50,324
Papa, your cuff links were not an omen.

877
00:29:50,408 --> 00:29:51,867
Her ankles are the
same size as her calves.

878
00:29:51,951 --> 00:29:53,495
Okay, if we're gonna
stay, we should probably

879
00:29:53,579 --> 00:29:55,629
figure out something else to be talking…

880
00:29:56,665 --> 00:29:58,208
We should go.

881
00:29:58,292 --> 00:29:59,709
Put the egg rolls in your purse.

882
00:29:59,793 --> 00:30:01,336
-My purse is silk.
-Fine.

883
00:30:01,420 --> 00:30:03,088
Anyone with pockets, grab a roll.

884
00:30:03,172 --> 00:30:05,006
-I'll get us a cab.
-We should walk.

885
00:30:05,090 --> 00:30:07,092
-I'm in heels.
-Fine, we're getting a cab.

886
00:30:07,176 --> 00:30:08,844
-Noah, get us a cab.
-Okay.

887
00:30:12,806 --> 00:30:14,391
[CAR HORN HONKS]

888
00:30:14,475 --> 00:30:16,267
ABE: Taxi!

889
00:30:16,351 --> 00:30:19,062
-NOAH: Taxi?
-ABE: Hey. Taxi!

890
00:30:19,146 --> 00:30:20,480
-JOEL: Midge.
-Joel, please…

891
00:30:20,564 --> 00:30:22,107
-I'm sorry.
-It's okay.

892
00:30:22,191 --> 00:30:24,025
-I didn't know you'd be here.
-How could you?

893
00:30:24,109 --> 00:30:26,152
-I didn't know you came here.
-We don't. We never have.

894
00:30:26,236 --> 00:30:27,904
I've been steering clear of
Barney Greengrass and Zabar's.

895
00:30:27,988 --> 00:30:29,823
I go all the way over to the East Side

896
00:30:29,907 --> 00:30:31,449
just to buy a pack of cigarettes.

897
00:30:31,533 --> 00:30:32,785
We're celebrating.
It's a special occasion.

898
00:30:32,869 --> 00:30:34,620
My father got a job at Bell Labs.

899
00:30:34,704 --> 00:30:37,331
Bell Labs? Wow, that's terrific.
He finally got it.

900
00:30:37,415 --> 00:30:38,666
It's a special occasion. That… That's all.

901
00:30:38,750 --> 00:30:39,834
I'll never come here again.

902
00:30:39,918 --> 00:30:41,043
We'll never come here again.

903
00:30:41,127 --> 00:30:42,795
I'm sorry. I just…

904
00:30:42,879 --> 00:30:45,256
I didn't mean to spoil the night.

905
00:30:45,340 --> 00:30:47,091
You didn't. It's…

906
00:30:57,477 --> 00:30:59,854
You should go back inside.

907
00:31:02,232 --> 00:31:07,069
Tell your… That's great

908
00:31:07,153 --> 00:31:09,364
about Bell Labs.

909
00:31:23,337 --> 00:31:25,380
ASTRID: And this is Rabbi Schneerson.

910
00:31:25,464 --> 00:31:27,382
A very good man, but
that card's in every pack,

911
00:31:27,466 --> 00:31:29,217
so no one will trade
you for him. [LAUGHS]

912
00:31:29,301 --> 00:31:30,761
ROSE: Capers and mustard.

913
00:31:30,845 --> 00:31:32,596
That's it for things I recognize in here.

914
00:31:32,680 --> 00:31:34,389
We should have taken the champagne.

915
00:31:34,473 --> 00:31:36,683
-It was already poured.
-That's why God invented funnels.

916
00:31:36,767 --> 00:31:38,351
No, wait, I see cottage cheese.

917
00:31:38,435 --> 00:31:40,520
-I like cottage cheese.
-[GASPS] You got a Hirchensohn!

918
00:31:40,604 --> 00:31:42,647
Chief rabbi of Hoboken!

919
00:31:42,731 --> 00:31:44,649
[LAUGHS] Have you ever
seen a Hirchensohn?

920
00:31:44,733 --> 00:31:46,777
To be honest, I've never
seen rabbi trading cards.

921
00:31:46,861 --> 00:31:48,320
Oh, one of the wonders of Israel.

922
00:31:48,404 --> 00:31:49,905
That and Shabbat on a kibbutz.

923
00:31:49,989 --> 00:31:51,741
Okay, this might be soup or gravy.
I don't know.

924
00:31:51,825 --> 00:31:53,159
It's a container of brown…
should we try it?

925
00:31:53,243 --> 00:31:55,328
This is no longer cottage cheese.

926
00:31:55,412 --> 00:31:57,288
ASTRID: I can't believe
someone actually came in here

927
00:31:57,372 --> 00:31:59,540
to steal the gefilte fish…
we could be eating that.

928
00:31:59,624 --> 00:32:02,001
-ROSE: Astonishing.
-You sure it's not here?

929
00:32:02,085 --> 00:32:04,003
-I looked.
-MIDGE: We looked.

930
00:32:04,087 --> 00:32:05,421
Can I go to bed now?

931
00:32:05,505 --> 00:32:06,964
-Oh…
-Of course, sweetie.

932
00:32:07,048 --> 00:32:09,342
Here, I'll take you.
Oh, and I can sneak in

933
00:32:09,426 --> 00:32:11,135
and steal a little kiss
for my baby Esther.

934
00:32:11,219 --> 00:32:13,095
Oh, no, uh, the baby
just went to sleep, Astrid.

935
00:32:13,179 --> 00:32:14,889
I promise you can
kiss her in the morning.

936
00:32:14,973 --> 00:32:16,724
Good night, Ethan. Sweet dreams.

937
00:32:16,808 --> 00:32:19,185
[GASPS] Cookies. I found cookies.

938
00:32:19,269 --> 00:32:20,728
Oh, ignore what your brother says

939
00:32:20,812 --> 00:32:23,564
-you are officially my favorite. Mmm.
-Mmm.

940
00:32:23,648 --> 00:32:25,066
It's not going to last.

941
00:32:25,150 --> 00:32:27,485
-What's not?
-Joel and that woman.

942
00:32:27,569 --> 00:32:30,197
I saw him check his watch. Twice.

943
00:32:30,281 --> 00:32:32,241
-Mama, don't…
-Trust me.

944
00:32:32,325 --> 00:32:35,161
That girl is on her way out.

945
00:32:43,836 --> 00:32:47,422
<i>♪ You with the stars in your eyes… ♪</i>

946
00:32:47,506 --> 00:32:50,676
Cookie for a smoke?

947
00:32:50,760 --> 00:32:53,804
If the parents catch
us, this was your idea.

948
00:32:53,888 --> 00:32:56,014
<i>-♪ You used to be ♪</i>
-Yeah, yeah.

949
00:32:56,098 --> 00:32:58,559
<i>-♪ Too wise ♪</i>
-[HORN HONKS IN DISTANCE]

950
00:33:01,687 --> 00:33:03,856
<i>♪ Hey there… ♪</i>

951
00:33:03,940 --> 00:33:06,149
What a dinner, huh?

952
00:33:06,233 --> 00:33:08,193
What? Did something unusual happen?

953
00:33:08,277 --> 00:33:09,946
I wasn't paying attention.

954
00:33:10,030 --> 00:33:12,031
I still can't believe you and Joel split.

955
00:33:12,115 --> 00:33:13,616
Wasn't my plan, believe me.

956
00:33:13,700 --> 00:33:15,618
It's so disappointing.
I really liked the guy.

957
00:33:15,702 --> 00:33:17,245
God, and that girl he was with.

958
00:33:17,329 --> 00:33:19,873
When I saw that, I
thought, "I should hit him."

959
00:33:19,957 --> 00:33:21,457
And I would've.

960
00:33:21,541 --> 00:33:23,877
But then I remembered
once we were joking around,

961
00:33:23,961 --> 00:33:25,879
and I sort of fake-punched his arm…

962
00:33:25,963 --> 00:33:27,338
Broke my pinkie.

963
00:33:27,422 --> 00:33:29,382
-What?
-He didn't look that big,

964
00:33:29,466 --> 00:33:31,384
but his arm was like a brick wall.

965
00:33:31,468 --> 00:33:33,720
-Yeah, he had strong arms.
-It was humiliating.

966
00:33:33,804 --> 00:33:35,805
The next day at work I
had to make up a story

967
00:33:35,889 --> 00:33:38,266
-about being mugged in the park.
-You never told me any of this.

968
00:33:38,350 --> 00:33:40,059
Well… it wasn't my most

969
00:33:40,143 --> 00:33:42,270
manly anecdote.

970
00:33:45,482 --> 00:33:48,653
I sure hate that he hurt you, boy.

971
00:33:49,904 --> 00:33:51,822
Thanks.

972
00:33:51,906 --> 00:33:53,908
Make sure the next
guy you get involved with

973
00:33:53,992 --> 00:33:55,409
has very weak upper body strength.

974
00:33:55,493 --> 00:33:57,202
-Of course.
-I'd like to defend your honor.

975
00:33:57,286 --> 00:33:59,121
-I'd appreciate that.
-But I have to be able

976
00:33:59,205 --> 00:34:01,081
to hold a pen the next day.

977
00:34:01,165 --> 00:34:03,751
Noah, listen, you got
to do me a favor, okay?

978
00:34:03,835 --> 00:34:04,960
Anything.

979
00:34:05,044 --> 00:34:06,545
Don't leave Astrid.

980
00:34:06,629 --> 00:34:08,172
Oh, my God. I'm not gonna leave Astrid.

981
00:34:08,256 --> 00:34:09,632
-She thinks you are.
-I'm not.

982
00:34:09,716 --> 00:34:11,425
I've told her a million times I'm not.

983
00:34:11,509 --> 00:34:13,218
-She's worried about h…
-Kids. I know, she's obsessed with it.

984
00:34:13,302 --> 00:34:15,679
I don't care if we have kids.
I want a dog.

985
00:34:15,763 --> 00:34:17,097
She's driving herself crazy.

986
00:34:17,181 --> 00:34:18,432
She's driving me crazy.

987
00:34:18,516 --> 00:34:19,850
I don't know what to do with her.

988
00:34:19,934 --> 00:34:21,101
